Jenkins is a popular open-source automation server used to automate the building, testing, and deployment of software. 
It is a central tool in the world of DevOps, specifically for implementing Continuous Integration (CI) and Continuous Delivery (CD) pipelines.
Core ConceptsCI/CD Hub: Jenkins acts as the "brain" of your development process, automatically triggering actions (like running tests) whenever code is updated in a repository like GitHub or Bitbucket.Automation Server: It replaces manual, repetitive tasks—such as compiling code or packaging applications—with automated "Jobs".Extensibility: With a library of over 1,800+ plugins, Jenkins can integrate with almost any tool in the software stack, including Docker, Kubernetes, Maven, and various cloud providers.Key FeaturesPipeline as Code: Using a Jenkinsfile, developers can define their entire build-and-deploy workflow in a script that lives alongside their code.Distributed Architecture: Jenkins uses a Controller-Agent (formerly Master-Slave) model, where a central controller manages tasks and distributes the actual work across multiple worker "agents" for faster execution.Platform Independent: It is written in Java, meaning it can run on Windows, Linux, and macOS.Why Use Jenkins?Early Bug Detection: Automated tests run with every commit, allowing teams to catch and fix bugs immediately.Faster Releases: Automation reduces human error and accelerates the time it takes to get code from a developer's machine to a production environment.Free and Community-Driven: 
As an open-source project with a massive user base, it is free to use and constantly updated by its community
